{"id": "667", "instruction": "Suppose a third-order matrix $A=\\left( \\begin{matrix} {{{1}}} & {{{1}}} & {{{0}}} \\\\ {{{-2}}} & {{{-1}}} & {{{-2}}} \\\\ {{{-1}}} & {{{-2}}} & {{{2}}} \\\\ \\end{matrix} \\right)$ , then what are $R(A)$ and $R(A^{*})$ respectively?\n\nOptions:\nA. $$R(A)=2 , R(A^{*})=3\n$$\nB. $$R(A)=2 , R(A^{*})=4\n$$\nC. $$R(A)=-3 , R(A^{*})=1\n$$\nD. $$R(A)=0 , R(A^{*})=2\n$$\nE. $$R(A)=3 , R(A^{*})=1\n$$\nF. $$R(A)=0 , R(A^{*})=1\n$$\nG. $$R(A)=1 , R(A^{*})=1\n$$\nH. $$R(A)=2 , R(A^{*})=1\n$$\nI. $$R(A)=0 , R(A^{*})=0\n$$", "output": "H"}
